---
// Print-optimized route for the 2-Hour Quote Checklist lead magnet.
// Open this URL in a browser → Cmd/Ctrl+P → Save as PDF.
// noindex so search engines don't pull the gated content directly.
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "The 2-Hour Quote Checklist — Printable PDF | Valley Clean Team";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description="Printable version of The 2-Hour Quote Checklist. 7 questions to ask before booking any cleaner."
  showNav={false}
  showFooter={false}
  schemaType="none"
  noindex={true}
>
  <style slot="preload">
    /* Brand tokens */
    :root {
      --pdf-cream: #f5efe6;
      --pdf-navy: #1b2a41;
      --pdf-brass: #c9a86b;
      --pdf-grey: #6b7280;
      --pdf-cream-deep: #ebe3d5;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      background: #d6cfc2;
      font-family:
        ui-serif,
        Georgia,
        "Times New Roman",
        serif;
    }

    .pdf-toolbar {
      max-width: 800px;
      margin: 24px auto 0;
      padding: 12px 20px;
      background: var(--pdf-navy);
      color: var(--pdf-cream);
      border-radius: 6px;
      font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
      font-size: 14px;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: space-between;
      gap: 12px;
    }
    .pdf-toolbar button {
      background: var(--pdf-brass);
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
      border: none;
      padding: 8px 16px;
      border-radius: 4px;
      font-weight: 600;
      cursor: pointer;
      font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
    }
    .pdf-toolbar button:hover {
      background: #b8975a;
    }
    .pdf-toolbar a {
      color: var(--pdf-cream);
      text-decoration: underline;
      font-size: 13px;
    }

    .pdf-page {
      max-width: 800px;
      margin: 16px auto 40px;
      background: #fff;
      padding: 56px 64px;
      border-radius: 6px;
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
      box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.06);
    }

    .pdf-overline {
      font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.18em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--pdf-brass);
      font-weight: 700;
      margin: 0 0 14px;
    }

    .pdf-title {
      font-size: 38px;
      line-height: 1.15;
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
      margin: 0 0 12px;
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
    }
    .pdf-subtitle {
      font-style: italic;
      font-size: 18px;
      line-height: 1.5;
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
      margin: 0 0 28px;
    }

    .pdf-rule {
      border: 0;
      height: 1px;
      background: var(--pdf-cream-deep);
      margin: 28px 0;
    }

    .pdf-page h2 {
      font-size: 22px;
      line-height: 1.25;
      font-weight: 700;
      margin: 32px 0 12px;
      letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    }
    .pdf-page h3 {
      font-size: 18px;
      font-weight: 700;
      margin: 22px 0 6px;
      line-height: 1.3;
    }
    .pdf-page p {
      font-size: 15.5px;
      line-height: 1.7;
      margin: 0 0 12px;
    }
    .pdf-page ul,
    .pdf-page ol {
      padding-left: 22px;
      margin: 8px 0 14px;
    }
    .pdf-page li {
      font-size: 15.5px;
      line-height: 1.6;
      margin: 6px 0;
    }
    .pdf-page strong {
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
    }
    .pdf-tip {
      background: var(--pdf-cream);
      border-left: 3px solid var(--pdf-brass);
      padding: 12px 16px;
      margin: 12px 0 18px;
      font-size: 14.5px;
      line-height: 1.6;
      border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;
    }
    .pdf-tip strong {
      color: var(--pdf-brass);
      letter-spacing: 0.04em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      font-size: 12px;
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 4px;
    }
    .pdf-check-item {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 14px;
      margin: 22px 0 0;
    }
    .pdf-check-item::before {
      content: "☐";
      color: var(--pdf-brass);
      font-size: 24px;
      line-height: 1;
      flex: 0 0 auto;
      /* Align the checkbox optically with the H3's cap-height, not its
         line box. The H3 has font-size 18px, line-height 1.3 → top of the
         glyph sits ~3px below the box top. Push the checkbox the same
         amount so the top of the box and the top of "1." line up. */
      margin-top: 3px;
    }
    .pdf-check-item .pdf-check-content {
      flex: 1;
      min-width: 0;
    }
    /* Inside a check item, the h3 already has the row's top margin from
       the parent, so kill its own top margin to keep the checkbox and the
       number on the same baseline. */
    .pdf-check-item .pdf-check-content > h3:first-child {
      margin-top: 0;
    }

    .pdf-quick-start {
      background: var(--pdf-navy);
      color: var(--pdf-cream);
      padding: 24px 28px;
      border-radius: 6px;
      margin: 24px 0;
    }
    .pdf-quick-start h2 {
      color: var(--pdf-cream);
      margin: 0 0 10px;
      font-size: 20px;
    }
    .pdf-quick-start p,
    .pdf-quick-start ol li {
      color: var(--pdf-cream);
      font-size: 15px;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    .pdf-footer {
      margin-top: 36px;
      padding-top: 24px;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--pdf-cream-deep);
      font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
      font-size: 12.5px;
      color: var(--pdf-grey);
      text-align: center;
      line-height: 1.7;
    }
    .pdf-footer strong {
      color: var(--pdf-navy);
    }

    /* Page-break hints (Astro v6 supports CSS3 print rules natively) */
    h2 {
      page-break-after: avoid;
    }
    .pdf-quick-start,
    .pdf-tip {
      page-break-inside: avoid;
    }

    /* Print rules — what gets sent to the printer */
    @media print {
      body {
        background: #fff;
      }
      .pdf-toolbar {
        display: none;
      }
      .pdf-page {
        box-shadow: none;
        max-width: 100%;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0 0 24px;
        border-radius: 0;
      }
      @page {
        margin: 0.6in;
        size: letter;
      }
    }
  </style>

  <div class="pdf-toolbar">
    <div>
      <strong>The 2-Hour Quote Checklist (printable)</strong> — press
      Ctrl/Cmd+P to save as PDF.
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:10px; align-items:center;">
      <a href="/checklist">← back to opt-in page</a>
      <button type="button" onclick="window.print()">Print / Save as PDF</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <main class="pdf-page">
    <p class="pdf-overline">The Valley Clean Team · Free PDF</p>
    <h1 class="pdf-title">The 2-Hour Quote Checklist</h1>
    <p class="pdf-subtitle">
      7 things to know before you book any cleaner — so you get a real price
      today, not a sales call on Thursday.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most cleaning quotes take three to five days. They start with a form,
      then a phone call, then a visit from someone in a marked vehicle, then
      an emailed estimate that's "starting at" some number you'll never
      actually pay.
    </p>
    <p>
      We built this checklist because that process is broken. You shouldn't
      have to take a Tuesday off work to find out what it costs to clean your
      house.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you use the seven items below, you can get a real, flat, all-in price
      — from us or anyone else — in under two hours. And you can be on the
      schedule today.
    </p>

    <div class="pdf-quick-start">
      <h2>Quick Start</h2>
      <p>
        If your house needs to be clean by tonight (showing tomorrow, in-laws
        on Friday, deposit walk-through Monday), do these three first:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Item 5</strong> — Have your square footage ready before you call</li>
        <li><strong>Item 7</strong> — Ask for a flat price, not "starting at"</li>
        <li><strong>Item 6</strong> — Confirm the same-day window in writing (text counts)</li>
      </ol>
      <p style="margin-bottom:0;">
        The other four items protect you from booking the wrong cleaner.
        These three get you on the schedule.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr class="pdf-rule" />

    <h2>Phase 1: Before You Call</h2>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>1. Decide what kind of clean you actually need</h3>
        <p>
          Cleaners price three things very differently. Knowing which one you
          need cuts your quote time in half.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Recurring</strong> — every week, every two weeks, or once
            a month. Lowest per-visit price (often 15–20% off the deep-clean
            rate).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Deep clean</strong> — for first visits, post-renovation,
            or any home that hasn't been professionally cleaned in 90+ days.
            Higher price, longer time on site.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Move-in / move-out</strong> — empty home, focus on
            appliances, baseboards, inside cabinets. Priced separately
            because the scope is different.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          If a cleaner won't tell you which category you fall into without a
          visit, that's a red flag. A real one can usually tell from a photo
          or a square-footage number.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>2. Write down your bedroom and bathroom count</h3>
        <p>
          Almost every legitimate cleaning quote uses bedrooms + bathrooms as
          the primary input. If you're calling, have it ready: "3 bed, 2
          bath, 2,200 square feet."
        </p>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          Half-baths count as half a bath. Most pricing rounds them up. Be
          honest — under-counting now means a surprise add-on later.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>3. Identify the deal-breaker rooms</h3>
        <p>Some rooms add real time and should be flagged before you get a quote:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>A separate primary bath with a soaker tub</li>
          <li>A finished basement with a second kitchen</li>
          <li>Two-story foyers or staircases needing a ladder</li>
          <li>Pet areas (litter, crates, rugs)</li>
          <li>A home office with electronics</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          Mention these up front. A cleaner who doesn't ask about them will
          either upcharge you on the day or rush through them. Both are bad.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="pdf-rule" />

    <h2>Phase 2: When You Call (or Text, or Click)</h2>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>4. Time the response</h3>
        <p>
          Open your phone clock when you submit the form, send the text, or
          hang up.
          <strong
            >A real local team responds in under 2 hours during business
            hours.</strong
          >
          Most chains take 24–72 hours. Aggregator apps (Homeaglow, Handy,
          Care.com) respond fast but match you with a different gig worker
          every time.
        </p>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          If they take longer than two hours to respond to a quote request,
          ask yourself — how long will they take to respond when something
          goes wrong on a clean?
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>5. Have your square footage ready</h3>
        <p>
          Look it up on Zillow, your closing docs, or the county property
          records — it takes 30 seconds. Without it, every cleaner will pad
          the quote to protect themselves.
        </p>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          Don't include garage square footage. Most cleaners don't service
          it.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>6. Get the arrival window in writing</h3>
        <p>
          A real same-day commitment is a window, not a vague "later today."
          For us it's a 2–4 hour arrival window after you accept the quote,
          sent to you by text. Anyone who says "we'll try to fit you in" is
          not actually offering same-day service.
        </p>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          Screenshot it. If they push back on putting an arrival window in a
          text, they don't really do same-day.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pdf-check-item">
      <div class="pdf-check-content">
        <h3>7. Ask for a flat price, not "starting at"</h3>
        <p>
          <strong
            >This is the single most important item on this list.</strong
          >
          The phrase "starting at $X" means "you will pay more than $X." A
          flat price means the number you saw is the number you pay.
        </p>
        <p>A real flat quote includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Labor for the entire clean</li>
          <li>Supplies and equipment</li>
          <li>Travel within the service area</li>
          <li>All the rooms you discussed</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          It does <strong>not</strong> include surprise "we needed extra
          time" add-ons. If a cleaner won't give you a flat number, ask why.
          The honest answer ("we haven't seen the home") tells you they need
          a visit before quoting — fine, but it's not same-day. The
          dishonest answer ("our prices vary") tells you to keep calling.
        </p>
        <div class="pdf-tip">
          <strong>Quick tip</strong>
          If you get a flat quote, get it in writing before they show up. A
          text with the price + arrival window is enough.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="pdf-rule" />

    <h2>Bonus: Three questions that reveal a serious cleaner</h2>
    <p>
      Once you have a quote, three more questions separate the pros from the
      rest:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>"Are you insured? For how much?"</strong> — A serious cleaner
        answers in dollars. Ours is $2 million. If they pause, they're
        either uninsured or under-insured. Either way, your homeowner's
        policy may not cover damage caused by an uninsured contractor.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>"Will the same team come every time?"</strong> — Aggregator
        apps and most large chains rotate cleaners. That means a stranger in
        your home every visit and inconsistent quality. A real local team
        sends the same crew so they learn your home.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>"Do I get photos of the finished clean?"</strong> —
        Photo-documented cleans are still rare. They're proof you got what
        you paid for, and they give you something concrete if anything is
        missed.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <hr class="pdf-rule" />

    <h2>What's Next</h2>
    <p>
      If you ran any cleaner through this checklist and they passed, book
      them. We mean it. The point of this checklist is not to sell you on us
      — it's to keep you from getting burned by the broken way most cleaning
      is sold.
    </p>
    <p>
      But if you're calling around and finding that nobody actually responds
      in two hours, nobody quotes flat, and nobody commits to a same-day
      window, that's because almost no insured, vetted local team does. We
      do.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong
        >Get a real flat quote in under 2 hours, with a same-day arrival
        window:</strong
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Alabama:</strong> (256) 826-1100</li>
      <li><strong>Tennessee:</strong> (615) 510-1427</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Online:</strong> thevalleycleanteam.com — quote form takes
        about 60 seconds
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="pdf-footer">
      <strong>The Valley Clean Team</strong><br />
      Veteran-owned. Women-led. $2M insured. Same team, every time.<br />
      Serving Huntsville, Athens, the Shoals, Birmingham, Mountain Brook,
      and Nashville.<br />
      — Todd &amp; Christen
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
